    "className": "mord mathnormal"
  }, "n")))))), mdx("p", null, "Richer areas of China and India are showing increasingly skewed female-male ratios, especially considering women's longevity and health relative to men after the age of 60. A worst-case example of high childbirth mortality rates is in Sub-Saharan Africa, which Amartya Sen referred in establishing female-male ratio as a baseline against which to compare other countries. In Pakistan, the ratio was ssomething like 0.91, whereas it's 1.02 in SSA. An estimated 44 million women missing in China according to the equation above. In quickly growing economies such as in New Delhi, even the under-5 population is showing huge disparities in girl-boy populations. Is the cause abortion? Infanticide? Are people simply slipping up due to their own beliefs, leading to higher female mortality?"), mdx("p", null, "One way to test this is to measure decrease in consumption of adult goods, such as cigarettes, when a family has a boy as opposed to a girl. This provides an effective way to discriminate consumption amongst family members, as opposed to the coarse approximations that would inevitably arise when attempting to gauge, at a distance, who gets what slice from the family pie."), mdx("p", null, "Deaton finds no evidence, in both Pakistan and the Ivory Coast, on beverage consumption for boys and girls being born. Families grow poorer (which we observe in the case of parents'/mothers' well-being after the Matlab experiment despite kids being equally well off)."), mdx("p", null, "#fill this in#^"), mdx("p", null, "Elaina Rose finds that droughts lead to higher girl mortality. Families give up their daughters. This doesn't explain the earlier results since richer places are weaning off of agriculture and thus susceptibility to drought."), mdx("p", null, "Household/Family Responsibility System (post-Mao) 1979, people free to grow cash crops. Women are valued more for their tea-picking abilities; men are valued more for their fruit-hauling abilities. If we compare years with high-tea production with their non-tea-growing, wheat-growing counterparts (serving as a counterfactual), we can calculate the difference-in-difference between the two areas. We can do the same with low-tea years."), mdx("p", null, "Proportion of women increased in areas where there was more tea sown; proportion of men increased in areas where there were more orchards. Mechanisms through which women \"proliferated\" more might involve adult women gaining more bargaining power and influencing birth, or men no longer choosing ", mdx("em", {
    parentName: "p"
  }, "against"), " having girls because they bring more economic value."), mdx("p", null, "Through what means do they enforce their preferences? Amniocentesis is more widely accessible to the richer parts of, say, India, and allows for gender identification in the womb. Sonography, its cheaper alternative, identifies gender 25% of the time, so that could also contribute to abortion. Oh, and we have literal fucking infanticide, and Chinese village chiefs proudly proclaiming that they haven't had a girl in half a decade."), mdx("p", null, "If there are fewer women, women are worth more where population doesn't grow so much, as in China. This doesn't apply as much to rapidly growing areas such as India, since the men will just shift to choosing younger women."), mdx("p", null, "Where women are scarce, savings are going up so that parents can afford the now more valuable bribe as well as an apartment for their son when he reaches marrying age."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, mdx("strong", {
    parentName: "p"
  }, "Ethics:")), mdx("p", null, "Why do we regulate experiments on human subjects?"), mdx("p", null, "Nazi research outed during the Nuremberg trials and the Tuskegee syphilis trials. The latter was performed by US health services over the course of 1932 to 1972. They chosee to observe, and not treat black American sharecroppers from Alabama. 28 died of syphilis, 100 died for related reasons, 40 wives infected, 19 children born with congenital syphilis. People were lured to get tested under the guise of these tests being treatment. This horrendous experiment was outed in 1972 and resulted in a $10m win against the PHS. Next to nothing was learned."), mdx("p", null, "What did we learn?"), mdx("p", null, "The victims lacked information and taken advantage of. They were lied to by a false incentive. They lacked a supportive infrastructure in an oppressive environment. They were ignorant and marginalized, poor and misled. Then there were the negative externalities, or shitty side effects, to their families."), mdx("p", null, "How do we determine whether or not an experiment is worthwhile? What risks and damage are we willing to take?"), mdx("p", null, "The National Commission for the Protection of Human Subjects of Biomedical and Behavioral Research put out the Belmont report, which details ethical principles and guidelines. These guidelines apply to human subjects irrespective of where or for what purpose data was collected. Human subject means someone whose information was collected through some intervention or interaction. Research implies the results translate into generalizable knowledge. ", "[consult slide]"), mdx("p", null, "Distinctions drawn between human subjects and firms, private and public data."), mdx("p", null, "What are these principles?"), mdx("p", null, "1) Respect for persons - autonomy, consent, privacy protection, safeguards from exploitation or coersion"), mdx("p", null, "2) Beneficence - maximize benefits, minimize risks. This is open to interpretation and not as mechanical as the previous principle. How do you evaluate risks to subjects or those affected by the research (externalities and spillover)? How do you maximize people's well-being when you know they're unwell?"), mdx("p", null, "3) Justice - Is the study equitable? If not, why?\n", "[consult book]"), mdx("p", null, "Online training available."), mdx("p", null, "Randomization in regards to these principles: it's considered unethical to harm people. In randomization, typically the primary concern is whether there is any harm caused to the treatment group or negative spillover effects."), mdx("p", null, "Randomization bias can occur if the method of inducing or incentivizing people to randomize or consent introduces bias. One amelioration is typically to make the inducement small enough that it doesn't make that much of a difference (avoiding undue inducement). In poor countries, not much inducement is typically needed."), mdx("p", null, mdx("strong", {
    parentName: "p"
  }, "Measurement:")), mdx("p", null, "We consult our theory of change to determine what we measure."), mdx("p", null, "We want to capture the factors that influence intermediate then final outcomes, as well as the general behaviors we're attempting to target. We can also control our measurements by including covariates in our regressions to increase precision (power, precision lecture). Additionally we can measure takeup, calculate ATT or CACE, and collect indicators that influence takeup. This also improves precision."), mdx("p", null, "We'd also want to account for differences in subgroups affected by the program (heterogeneous treatment effects)."), mdx("p", null, "We want to see how generalizable the program is, and if the local conditions are similar."), mdx("p", null, mdx("em", {
    parentName: "p"
  }, "Woman as Policymakers (India):")), mdx("p", null, "After India amended its federal government in 1992, power over local development programs transferred from states to Gram Panchayats, or village councils. These councils were made to reserve a third of their seating for women. Assignment of seats and positions was scheduled randomly by the government."), mdx("p", null, "These Panchayats make decisions in 29 development-related areas, such as maternity care, child care, infrastructure, education, etc. Council members, or councilors, are elected every 5 years, and from among themselves elect a chairperson. The aim of this system brought about by the 73rd amendment was to decentralize these decisions."), mdx("p", null, "Because Panchayats can cover large swaths of the population, it's mandated that they hold a general assembly every half a year to a year. They announce what they'd worked on and propose how they wish to spend their budget moving forward. They also regularly have office hours during which people can put forth requests and complaints."), mdx("p", null, "So we measure the effects of the randomly assigned seats reserved for women in these Panchayats."), mdx("p", null, "What are the assumptions and categories in this theory of change, and how can we measure them? Will reserved seats be filled? Will the democratic process play out as intended in order to observe the desired effect? What ", mdx("em", {
    parentName: "p"
  }, "is"), " the desired effect? If women are policymakers, will they effect changes geared more towards women, and how likely is that to happen?"), mdx("p", null, "Kelsey Jack assumes that we will get public goods in line with women's preferences as a result of the \"woman as policymakers\" program. This presupposes that those preferences are both voiced and represented, and has to take into account whether or not there is something preventing the women from effecting these changes."), mdx("p", null, "We want to measure components of this theory of change, such as measuring women's versus men's preferences, how investments are allocated and if they reflect typical investments, say at home. We can also look at the public budget just to see how that's been working out."), mdx("p", null, "We want send out enumerators to understand issue priorities between men and women, and going off of the areas where these priorities differ (e.g. women valuing drinking water more than men), compare differences in those areas in quota versus non-quota villages."), mdx("p", null, mdx("strong", {
